{{Infobox person | name = Abby Leach | image = Abby Leach.jpg | alt = Abby Leach | caption = Abby Leach | other_names = | occupation = American classical scholar | birth_date = {{start-date|1855|mf=yes}} | death_date = {{Death-date and age|1918|1855|mf=yes}} | birth_place = | death_place = }}
'''Abby Leach''' (1855–1918) was a Professor of Greek and Latin at [[Vassar College]] in [[Poughkeepsie, New York]] from 1883 until her death.
She was one of the first female students at [[Harvard University]], enrolling in a "Plan for Private Collegiate Instruction of Women" upon its establishment in 1879 at her behest. The "Plan" led to the later establishment of [[Radcliffe College]]. Because Harvard at that time did not grant degrees to women, Vassar College granted her bachelor's and master's degrees after they appointed her to the Vassar faculty.<ref name="Briggs">{{cite book |last=Briggs |first=Ward|title= Abby Leach (1855-1918)|date=|publisher= The Classical World, Vol. 90, No. 2/3 (Nov 1996 – Feb 1997), Six Women Classicists, pp. 97–105 }}</ref>
She was a member of the Greek Conference of the [[Committee of Ten]] called by the [[National Education Association]] in 1894, the only female member of any conference of the Committee of Ten.<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=Report of the Committee of Ten on Secondary School Studies: With the Reports of the Conferences Arranged by the Committee|author=National Education Association of the United States. Committee of Ten on Secondary School Studies|date=1894|publisher=National Educational Association|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PfcBAAAAYAAJ|page=3|accessdate=2015-04-08}}</ref>
In 1899, she became the first female [[List of Presidents of the American Philological Association|president of the American Philological Association]].<ref name="Briggs"/> From 1899 to 1901, Leach was president of the [[Association of Collegiate Alumnae]] which later became the [[American Association of University Women]].
