{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = Doctor | name = Moritz Brosch | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1829|4|7|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Prague]], [[Bohemia]], [[Austrian Empire]] | disappeared_date = <!-- {{Disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} (disappeared date then birth date) --> | disappeared_place = | disappeared_status = | death_date = {{Death date and age|1907|7|14|1829|4|7|df=y}} | death_place = [[Venice]], [[Veneto]], [[Kingdom of Italy (1861–1946)|Kingdom of Italy]] | death_cause = | body_discovered = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline}} --> | monuments = | residence = | nationality = | other_names = | citizenship = | education = [[Journalism]] | alma_mater = | occupation = [[Historian]], [[Journalist]] | years_active = | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = | notable_works = | style = | influences = | influenced = | home_town = }} '''Moritz Brosch''' (7 April 1829 – 14 July 1907) was a [[German Bohemian]] [[historian]] and professional [[English people|English]] scholar.<ref>{{Cite journal|jstor = 550147|title = Moritz Brosch|journal = The English Historical Review|volume = 22|issue = 88|pages = 758–760|last1 = Ward|first1 = A. W|year = 1907}}</ref> He was born on 7 April 1829 in [[Prague]], [[Bohemia]], [[Austrian Empire]] which is now in the [[Czech Republic]]. He was educated in Prague and [[Vienna]], and became a [[journalist]]. Later he devoted himself to historical study, and he died on 14 July 1907 at [[Venice]], where he had resided for over thirty years.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AqM8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA199 | title=The German Historians and England: A Study in Nineteenth-Century Views| isbn=9780521080637| last1=McLelland| first1=Charles E| date=1971-09-30}}</ref>
== Works == To the series ''Geschichte der europäischen Staaten'' Brosch contributed ''[[England]] 1509–1550'' (6 vols., Gotha, 1884–1899), a continuation of the work of [[Johann Martin Lappenberg|J.M. Lappenberg]] and [[Reinhold Pauli|R. Pauli]], and ''Der Kirchenstaat'' (Gotha, 1880–1882). He gave further proof of his interest in English history by writing ''[[Lord Bolingbroke]] und die [[British Whig Party|Whigs]] und [[Tories]] seiner Zeit'' (Frankfort, 1883), and ''[[Oliver Cromwell]] und die [[puritan]]ische Revolution'' (Frankfort, 1886). He also wrote ''[[Pope Julius II|Julius II.]] und die Gründung des Kirchenstaats'' (Gotha, 1878), while one of his last pieces of work was to contribute a chapter on "The height of the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] power" to vol. iii of the ''[[Cambridge Modern History]]'' (1904).
